Edited web/src/components/health/health-helper.ts (9 lines -> 6 lines)### Group 6: Fix Tooltip `appendTo="inline"` - string no longer accepted
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  ▸ shell
    command: cd web && grep -rn 'appendTo="inline"' src/ --include="*.tsx" --include="*.ts"

src/components/dropdowns/table-display-options.tsx:33:        <Tooltip content={t('Force table rows to specific sizing.')} appendTo="inline">
src/components/dropdowns/table-display-options.tsx:64:          appendTo="inline"Let me check what the PF6 Tooltip `appendTo` prop accepts:
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  ▸ shell
    command: cd web && grep -A5 "appendTo" node_modules/@patternfly/react-core/dist/esm/components/Tooltip/Tooltip.d.ts 2>/dev/null | head -10

    appendTo?: HTMLElement | ((ref?: HTMLElement) => HTMLElement);
    /**
     * aria-labelledby or aria-describedby for tooltip.
     * The trigger will be cloned to add the aria attribute, and the corresponding id in the form of 'pf-tooltip-#' is added to the content container.
     * If you don't want that or prefer to add the aria attribute yourself on the trigger, set aria to 'none'.
     */So in PF6 `appendTo` no longer accepts `"inline"` as a string. The `"inline"` value in PF5 meant "append to parent element". Let me check the actual build error more carefully - the error is about `appendTo` on `Tooltip`:

Looking at the error message again:
```
TS2322: Type 'string' is not assignable to type 'HTMLElement | ((ref?: HTMLElement | undefined) => HTMLElement) | undefined'.
```

The fix is to remove `appendTo="inline"` or change it to use a function that returns the parent element. Since the `"inline"` behavior was just to append the tooltip to the parent, the simplest fix is to use `appendTo={() => document.body}` or just remove it entirely:
